revision.text:
{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}} {{Infobox language |name=’Ole |altname=''’Olekha'', ''Monkha'', ''Monpa'', ''Ole Mönpa'' |nativename=Black Mountain Monpa |region=[[Bhutan]] |speakers=500 |date=2007 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Sino-Tibetan |script=[[Tibetan script]] |iso3=ole |glotto=olek1239 |glottorefname=Olekha }} [[File:Rindzi Phup.gif|thumb|250px|right|Rindzi Phup, one of the last speakers of the 'Ole Mönpa language. Photo by [[George van Driem]]|alt=Rindzi Phup, one of the last speakers of the 'Ole Mönpa language]]
'''{{'}}Ole''', also called '''{{'}}Olekha''' or '''Black Mountain [[Monpa people|Monpa]]''', is a [[Sino-Tibetan languages|Sino-Tibetan language]] spoken by about 1,000 people in the [[Black Mountains (Bhutan)|Black Mountains]] of [[Wangdue Phodrang District|Wangdue Phodrang]] and [[Trongsa District]]s in western [[Bhutan]]. The term 'Ole refers to a clan of speakers.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Center of Nepal and Asian Studies Journal |title=In Quest of Mahākirānti |last=van Driem |first=George |author-link=George van Driem |volume=19 |number=2 |pages=241–247 |url=http://www.thlib.org/static/reprints/contributions/CNAS_19_02_05.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=2011-10-23 |date=July 1992}}</ref>
==Locations== According to the ''[[Ethnologue]]'', Olekha is spoken in the following locations of [[Bhutan]]. *[[Trongsa District]]: 3 enclaves west of Mangde river *[[Wangdue Phodrang District]]: Adha, Jangji, Rukha, Thrumzur, and Wangling villages
Dialects are separated by the [[Black Mountains (Bhutan)|Black Mountains]].
==Varieties== Black Mountain Monpa is spoken in at least 6 villages. The variety spoken in Rukha village, south-central Wangdi is known as ’Olekha.<ref name="Hyslop2016">Gwendolyn Hyslop. 2016. Worlds of knowledge in Central Bhutan: Documentation of 'Olekha. Language Documentation & Conservation 10. 77-106.</ref> Out of a population of 100-150 people (about 15 households) in Rukha village, there is only one elderly female fluent speaker and two semi-fluent speakers of ’Olekha.<ref name="Hyslop2016"/>
George van Driem (1992)<ref>van Driem, George. 1992. ''The Monpa language of the Black Mountains''. Presented at ICSTLL 25.</ref> reports a Western dialect (spoken in Rukha and Reti villages) and Eastern dialect (spoken in Cungseng village).
==History== 'Ole was unknown beyond its immediate area until 1990,{{Citation needed|date=October 2014}} and is now highly endangered, and was originally assumed to be [[East Bodish languages|East Bodish]].<ref name=BlenchPost13>Blench, R. & Post, M. W. (2013). [https://www.academia.edu/627686/Rethinking_Sino-Tibetan_phylogeny_from_the_perspective_of_North_East_Indian_languages Rethinking Sino-Tibetan phylogeny from the perspective of Northeast Indian languages]</ref> [[George van Driem]] described 'Ole as a remnant of the primordial population of the Black Mountains before the southward expansion of the ancient East Bodish tribes.<ref name=vanDriem93>{{cite web|url=http://repository.forcedmigration.org/pdf/?pid=fmo:3003 |format=PDF |last=van Driem |first=George L. |author-link=George van Driem |title=Language Policy in Bhutan |publisher=[[SOAS, University of London]] |location=[[London]] |year=1993 |accessdate=2011-01-18 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101101084255/http://repository.forcedmigration.org/pdf/?pid=fmo%3A3003 |archivedate=1 November 2010 |deadurl=no |df=dmy }}</ref>
More recently, Gwendolyn Hyslop (2016),<ref name="Hyslop2016"/> agreeing with van Driem, has suggested that 'Ole is an isolated Sino-Tibetan language heavily influenced by [[East Bodish languages|East Bodish]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=van Driem |first=George L. |author-link=George van Driem |title=Tibeto-Burman subgroups and historical grammar |journal=Himalayan Linguistics Journal |volume=10 |issue=1 |year=2011 |pages=31–39 |url=http://www.linguistics.ucsb.edu/HimalayanLinguistics/articles/2011/HLJ1001B.html |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120112220623/http://www.linguistics.ucsb.edu/HimalayanLinguistics/articles/2011/HLJ1001B.html |archivedate=12 January 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> Because of its small amount of cognates with East Bodish languages, Blench and Post provisionally treat 'Ole as an isolate.<ref name=BlenchPost13/>
==External relationships== The distantly related [[Tshangla language]] of eastern Bhutan, also called "Monpa" and predating Dzongkha, also belongs to the [[Sino-Tibetan languages]].<ref name=vanDriem93/><ref name=vanDriem1>{{cite book |first=George |last=van Driem |author-link=George van Driem |year=2001 |title=Languages of the Himalayas: An Ethnolinguistic Handbook of the Greater Himalayan Region |publisher=Brill |pages=915 ''et seq.''}}</ref> Although 'Ole is most closely related to the [[Bumthang language]], both being [[East Bodish languages]], Tshangla and related languages form a sister branch not to the East Bodish group, but to its parent [[Bodish languages|Bodish branch]]. Thus the ambiguous term "Monpa" risks separating languages that should be grouped together, while grouping languages together that are quite separate.<ref name=Andvik>{{cite book |title=A Grammar of Tshangla |volume=10 |publisher=[[Brill Publishers]] |series=Tibetan Studies Library |first=Erik E. |last=Andvik |year=2010 |pages=4–7 |isbn=9004178279}}</ref>
Gerber (2018)<ref>Gerber, Pascal. 2018. ''[https://www.academia.edu/36564118/Areal_features_in_Gongduk_Bjokapakha_and_Black_Mountain_M%C3%B6npa_phonology_Draft_ Areal features in Gongduk, Bjokapakha and Black Mountain Mönpa phonology]''. Unpublished draft.</ref> notes that Black Mountain Mönpa has had extensive contact with [[Gongduk language|Gongduk]] before the arrival of [[East Bodish languages]] in [[Bhutan]]. The following comparative vocabulary table from Gerber (2018: 13-16) compares Gongduk, Black Mountain Mönpa, and Bjokapakha, which is a divergent [[Tshangla language|Tshangla]] variety.
