[[File:Ioannis Logothetis.jpg|thumb|150px|right|Ioannis Logothetis, ''proestos'' of [[Livadeia]], by [[Louis Dupré (painter)|Louis Dupré]]]] The '''kodjabashis''' ({{lang-el|κοτζαμπάσηδες|kotzabasides}}; singular κοτζάμπασης, ''kotzabasis''; {{lang-sh|kodžobaša, kodžabaša}}; from {{lang-tr|kocabaṣı, hocabaṣı}}) were local Christian notables in parts of the [[Ottoman Balkans]], most often referring to [[Ottoman Greece]]{{sfn|Stavrianos|2000|p=273}}{{sfn|Zakythenos|1976|p=}} and especially the [[Peloponnese]]. They were also known in Greek as ''proestoi'' or ''prokritoi'' (προεστοί/πρόκριτοι, "primates") or ''demogerontes'' (δημογέροντες, "elders of the people"). In some places they were elected (such in the islands for example), but, especially in the Peloponnese, they soon became a hereditary [[oligarchy]], who exercised considerable influence and held posts in the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] administration.{{sfn|Stavrianos|2000|p=273}}
The title was also present in [[Ottoman Serbia]] and [[Bosnia Eyalet|Bosnia]],<ref>{{cite book|author=Hannes Grandits|title=Herrschaft und Loyalität in der spätosmanischen Gesellschaft: das Beispiel der multikonfessionellen Herzegowina|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cPcvUev25p4C&pg=PA564|year=2008|publisher=Böhlau Verlag Wien|isbn=978-3-205-77802-8|pages=564–}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Jahrbücher für Geschichte und Kultur Südosteuropas: JGKS|volume=8–10|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lFAsAQAAIAAJ|year=2006|publisher=Slavica Verlag|p=92}}</ref> where it was known as ''starešina'' ("elder, chief") instead of the official Turkish name.<ref>{{cite book|author=Milenko S. Filipović|title=Among the people, native Yugoslav ethnography: selected writing of Milenko S. Filipović|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tuLYAAAAMAAJ|year=1982|publisher=Michigan Slavic Publications, Dept. of Slavic Languages and Literatures|p=261}}</ref> The terms ''[[chorbaji]]'' (from Turkish ''çorbacı'') and ''[[Knez (title)|knez]]'' (a Slavic title) were also used for this type of primates, in Bulgaria and Serbia respectively.{{sfn|Stavrianos|2000|p=224}}
The equivalent of the kodjabashis in Orthodox villages was the ''[[mukhtar]]'' in Muslim villages, while mixed villages had both.<ref>{{cite book|title=Simpozijum Seoski dani Sretena Vukosavljevića: 14., 15. i 16. jun 1974. godine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DvBTAAAAYAAJ|year=1974|publisher=Opštinskȧ zajednica obrazovanja|p=98|quote=<!--На челу муслиманског села стајао је муктар (односно кмет), а у пра- вославним насел>има ове послове је обавл>ао коџобаша (кмет). У ме- шовитим селима постојали су паралелно и муктар (за муслимане) и коџобаша (за хришћане). Муктар, односно коџобаша, представл>а- ју почетну управну степеницу у државној управи, коју је углавном село бирало на јавном окупу. Некако ад балканских ратова наовамо и за муктара и за коџобашу је прихваћен општи ...-->}}</ref>
During the [[Greek War of Independence]], the antagonism between the Peloponnesian kodjabashis, who sought to retain their previous preponderance and power, and the military leaders drawn from the [[klephts]], was one of the main driving forces behind the outbreak of the [[Greek civil wars of 1824–1825]], in which the "aristocratic" faction comprising the kodjabashis, the wealthy shipowners of [[Hydra Island|Hydra]] and the [[Phanariotes]], prevailed.<ref>{{cite book | title=A Concise History of Greece | edition=Revised | first = Richard | last = Clogg | authorlink = Richard Clogg | publisher = Cambridge University Press | year = 2002 | isbn = 0521004799 | pages =35ff.}}</ref>
