'''Sexual frustration''' in humans is frustration caused by a discrepancy between a person's desired and achieved [[Human sexual activity|sexual activity]]. It may result from a variety of circumstances including physical, mental, emotional, social, or religious/spiritual barriers. It may also derive from not being satisfied during sex, which may be due to issues such as [[anorgasmia]], [[anaphrodisia]], [[premature ejaculation]], [[delayed ejaculation]],<ref>{{cite journal |last=Hatzimouratidis |first=Konstantinos |displayauthors=1 |first2=Edouard |last2=Amar |first3=Ian |last3=Eardley |first4=Francois |last4=Giuliano |first5=Dimitrios |last5=Hatzichristou |first6=Francesco |last6=Montorsi |first7=Yoram |last7=Vardi |first8=Eric |last8=Wespes |title=Guidelines on male sexual dysfunction: erectile dysfunction and premature ejaculation |journal=European Urology |volume=57 |issue=5 |year=2010 |pages=804–814 |doi=10.1016/j.eururo.2010.02.020 }}</ref> [[erectile dysfunction]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2009/feb/11/prisonsandprobation-sexual-health |title=Erwin James: Sexual frustration plagues prison life &#124; Comment is free |publisher=theguardian.com |date=2011-09-20 |accessdate=2014-07-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Winch |first=Guy |url=http://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/the-squeaky-wheel/201109/marriage-and-sexual-frustrations-inevitable-or-solvable |title=Marriage and Sexual Frustrations: Inevitable or Solvable? |publisher=Psychology Today |date=2011-09-20 |accessdate=2014-07-13}}</ref> or an incompatibility or discrepancy in libido.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Reece |first=Rex |title=Causes and Threatments of Sexual Desire Discrepancies in Male Couples |journal=Journal of Homosexuality |volume=14 |issue=1–2 |year=1987 |pages=157–172 |doi=10.1300/J082v14n01_12 }}</ref>
Sexual frustration can result from an individual's lacking one or more of the organs needed for sexual release but still having one or more of the organs that cause a sex-drive. For males it could be that they have testicles and no penis; a male might be born without a penis ([[aphallia]]) or be born with one and have it removed ([[penis removal]] or [[penectomy]]). Men can still ejaculate via [[prostate]] stimulation in that case. For females they might not have a clitoris which causes sexual pleasure; a female might have had her clitoris forcibly severed ([[female genital mutilation]]) or voluntarily removed (female [[Circumcision|circumcusion]]) as part of a medical procedure.
[[Involuntary celibacy]] is a form of sexual frustration.<ref>[https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/blog/minority-report/201706/involuntary-celibacy Involuntary Celibacy] Published by [[Psychology Today]] on June 21, 2017</ref>
