{{Infobox baseball biography |name=Wattie Holm |position=[[Outfielder]] |image=WattieHolmGoudeycard.jpg |bats=Right |throws=Right |birth_date={{Birth date|1901|12|28|mf=y}} |birth_place=[[Peterson, Iowa]] |death_date={{death date and age|1950|5|19|1901|12|28}} |death_place=[[Everly, Iowa]] |debutleague = MLB |debutdate=April 15 |debutyear={{Baseball year|1924}} |debutteam=[[St. Louis Cardinals]] |finalleague = MLB |finaldate=August 8 |finalyear={{Baseball year|1932}} |finalteam=[[St. Louis Cardinals]] |statleague = MLB |stat1label=[[Batting average]] |stat1value=.275 |stat2label=[[Home runs]] |stat2value=6 |stat3label=[[Runs batted in]] |stat3value=174 |teams= *[[St. Louis Cardinals]] ({{Baseball year|1924}}–{{Baseball year|1929}}, {{baseball year|1932}}) }} '''Roscoe Albert Holm''' (December 28, 1901 – May 19, 1950) was a [[Major League Baseball]] player. Holm played for the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] in his seven-year career. He played from {{Baseball year|1924}} to {{Baseball year|1932}}, missing the {{Baseball year|1930}} and {{Baseball year|1931}} seasons. Holm was also a member of the Cardinals first World Series in [[1926 World Series|1926]]. He batted and threw right-handed.
Holm was born in [[Peterson, Iowa]], and died in 1950 in [[Everly, Iowa]]. He committed [[suicide]] by shooting himself, after shooting his wife.<ref>{{cite news |title=Waddy Holm Kills Wife, Injures Child And Ends His Life |newspaper=Syracuse Post-Standard |date=May 20, 1950 |page=6 |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/21285537/waddy_holms_kills_wife_injures_child/ |via=[[Newspapers.com]] }}</ref>
